1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:02,653
Titanic had enough lifeboats to satisfy the law.

2
00:00:03,434 --> 00:00:04,714
That sentence sounds safe.

3
00:00:05,575 --> 00:00:08,337
In 1912, it was the problem.

4
00:00:09,619 --> 00:00:12,002
British rules measured lifeboats by tonnage.

5
00:00:12,882 --> 00:00:18,987
Above 10,000 tons, the top bracket required 16 lifeboats for 990 people.

6
00:00:19,888 --> 00:00:26,495
Titanic carried 16 lifeboats and four collapsibles, enough for about 1,176 people.

7
00:00:27,396 --> 00:00:30,038
More than 2,200 were aboard.

8
00:00:30,018 --> 00:00:31,580
The paperwork said compliant.

9
00:00:32,262 --> 00:00:33,363
The ship said otherwise.

10
00:00:34,164 --> 00:00:35,527
Some boats left underfilled.

11
00:00:36,189 --> 00:00:37,231
The law failed one way.

12
00:00:37,832 --> 00:00:39,234
Evacuation failed another.

13
00:00:40,316 --> 00:00:42,500
Afterward, investigators pushed the correction.

14
00:00:43,161 --> 00:00:45,304
Count people carried, not tonnage.

15
00:00:46,347 --> 00:00:50,514
Two years later, SOLAS turned that lesson into international rulemaking.

16
00:00:51,375 --> 00:00:55,182
The old category kept measuring yesterday's ship while approving tomorrow's risk.

17
00:00:55,984 --> 00:00:59,350
Small causes, massive consequences.
